msIdentifier.repository: Pembroke College Library: on long-term deposit at Cambridge University Library

additions.p: Rear pastedown: Monostich added in ink (Walther 27937), and a large quantity of notes in faded plummet / drypoint.

binding.p: Original, repaired by Douglas Cockerell Cockerell, Douglas and Son, 1975: tawed skin over thick, flush, chamfered oak boards; sewn on three bands, not raised on the flat spine; square-shouldered tabs at each end of the spine, once with blue cloth lining and blue overstitching; title in capitals up the spine; two marks of chain-staples at the foot of the front cover; formerly a strap of thick ?pink-stained skin from a recess in the front board to a pin at the rear. There was once an overcover.

history.origin:
Mid-12th century. England, Bury St Edmunds.
The manuscript was made and kept at the Abbey of Bury St Edmunds Abbey of Bury St. Edmunds .
CBMLC 4, B13.145

provenance.p: Pressmark (B.92), written by the hand of Henry Kirkestede (c. 1314-c. 1379) Kirkestede, Henry, approximately 1314-approximately 1378 (f. 1r).

history.acquisition: Presumably given to Pembroke College, Cambridge Pembroke College in 1599 by William Smart (d. 1599) Smart, William, portreeve of Ipswich, -1599 , though it is not recorded by Thomas James or Matthew Wren. The College bookplate is pasted onto the front pastedown.

recordHist.source: This catalogue entry draws on the description provided by Rodney M. Thomson, A descriptive catalogue of the medieval manuscripts at Pembroke College, Cambridge (2022) (used here by kind permission of the author).

availability.p: Researchers should note that Pembroke College's western European medieval manuscripts are housed at Cambridge University Library (CUL). Scholars who wish to consult Pembroke College manuscripts should contact the Manuscripts Reading Room at CUL to arrange their visit; all CUL admissions procedures will apply. For information on eligibility and admissions procedures, see Joining the Library. For further information on the availability of the manuscript, please contact the Manuscripts Reading Room.

seg.seg: Introductory text (ff. 1-2): frame and lines ruled neatly in crayon, 49 lines, written above top line, in two columns.

Text: in the second of three columns, in the middle of the page, frame and lines ruled carelessly in crayon, with line ruling ad hoc and independent of the other columns. 17-18 lines, written above top line, in larger script on every third line. Until f. 54, the text column is roughly 70mm in width, and variable thereafter.

layout.seg: Gloss: Ruled in two columns with crayon on either side of the text column, for approximately 39-46 lines of gloss written above top line (though not all lines accommodate a gloss), with the lines ruled ad hoc and independently of the text column and one another. Until f. 54, the gloss columns are roughly 65mm and 60mm in width, and variable thereafter.

handNote.p: Text and gloss are each written by a single English scribe, in protogothic bookhand. The gloss hand wrote the material on ff. 1-2.
Folios 87r-88v are written by a different scribe, also in protogothic bookhand.

decoNote.p: A large L outlined in the same ink as used for the text, intended for colouring but left unfilled, with the accompanying display script also lacking and presumably also intended to be coloured (f. 3r).
Red or green initials, some ornamented in one or both colours (ff. 1-85).
Passages of gloss begin with large paraphs in the same ink as used for the text.

note.p: Frequent additional glossing in small note-hands of the 13th century.

list.item: Quire 16five: perhaps originally a quire of 8 leaves. First leaf conjoint with rear pastedown; second leaf a singleton, stub remains of counterpart leaf, probably an excised blank; ?two leaves missing after f. 114; ff. 115-116 a bifolium stitched in separately.

seg.seg: Text: in the second of three columns, in the middle of the page, frame and lines ruled in crayon, ruled independently of the gloss columns. 19 lines, written above top line, in larger script on every third line.

layout.seg: Gloss: Ruled in two columns with crayon on either side of the text column, for approximately 42-49 lines of gloss written above top line (though not all lines accommodate a gloss), with the lines ruled independently of the text column and one another.

handNote.p: Text and gloss are each written by a single English scribe, in protogothic bookhand. The gloss hand wrote the material on ff. 115v-117v.

decoNote.p: A very few initials in red and/or green, sometimes with modest ornament.
